snippet.textDisplay:
I love Rise of Skywalker. I could see why many people wouldn't, but none of those touchy details ever bothered me. I, too, thought Rey and Ben would have some kind of sibling relationship but I didn't put my money on it, and I couldn't help but feel giddy during their final moment together. (Honestly, I totally forgot about the possibility of them being siblings when I walked into the theater.) I also had a hunch that Palpatine had something to do with Snoke's existence. My first guess was that Snoke was gonna be a temporary back-up leader until Palpatine came into power again. And Rey adopting the Skywalker name? I thought it was fitting considering what went into her success at the end of the movie. I wasn't confused by anything in the story because either I didn't care or think it was important, or it personally made sense to me.


On another note, I can't help but think that, if I'm not missing any jokes here, the assumptions that were made by you are pretty ridiculous, such as the idea that Lando was flirting with the ex-Stormtrooper woman when he clearly wasn't. (I've actually noticed some ridiculous assumptions slowly appearing more and more in your recent reviews. What gives, dude?)

snippet.textDisplay:
A lot of the new trilogy’s problems can be traced directly to Rey. She was designed to be “an icon for girls” by rainbow-haired third-wavers who think invincibility is the same as character. Luke Skywalker was a traveler on the Hero’s Journey in the classical style, and had to be destroyed to be replaced with Rey, since replacing classic heroes instead of making new ones is just what’s done in current year. And having destroyed Luke, the writers have Rey declaim that she is the new Skywalker.

The audience that grew up with this, having heard the rants directed at them as “toxic fans”, aren’t in the slightest inclined to take it.

Sprinkle in a bit of Chinese market racism pandering, and you’ve got a recipe for failure.

snippet.textDisplay:
The movie is not the best in the franchise, but for me it is also far from the worst. JJ's camera movement is amazing (better than Rian Johnson's cuts). Sure, the story could be better, but a little to blame is, in my view, from the predecessor movie. There are people who keep talking about bad moments from episode 9 and idolize 8, but 8 also has a lot of bad things, like Snoke's ridiculous death, the useless adventure in Canto Bight, Rey's [nonexistent] training in Ahch-To. , too simplistic fights (forget that force exists), and the complete inconsistency of First Order superiority, since the entire Starkiller base had been destroyed moments before ...
9 has bad things, but it flows in a way that entertains more.

snippet.textDisplay:
Wishful thinking scene. Please reply if you like!

At the end of Rise of Skywalker when Rey is burying the light sabers she is approached by two teens dressed reminiscent of Rey at the beginning of her journey (like  scavengers). They ask Rey if she would like to buy some krayt dragon skin for the Sun's have started their decent and the temperature is beginning to drops low. 'Aren't you cold'? She hears.

Rey feels a cold chill she hadn't felt even with the two Sun's Setting but says no thank you and asks the teens (one boy and a slightly older girl) what are your names to which the girl impulsively replies Mara with the inattentive boy not answer as he's too busy roaming around in his satchel for an item to sell. Mara states 'he's my kid brother and he won't stop until he's found something you'll want to buy, he once sold a jar of sinking sand from.the swallowlands to a retired Hutt guard'.

'Well tell him I won't be needing any sand there's plenty around' Rey says with a smirk. 'Who are you?' asks Mara. Pausing first she replies I'm Rey. Rey Skywalker.

She turns to watch the Suns setting and with the teens behind her and the memories of people she has lost along the way Leia and Luke particularly, in mind Rey whispers 'May the Force' suddenly Mara finishes Ray's sentence out loud saying 'Be with you' And asks her brother 'we've heard that before haven't we?' looking over to where he is.

Rey feeling a double intrusion of her mind that she hadn't noticed and finding it hard to block rises to her feet and backs away a pace from the teens. Mara exclaims 'I'm sorry if I frightened you I can tell sometimes if people are frightened, please let me start again. I'm Mara Antilles, and this is'...

Still startled by not being able to block her mind intrusion Rey Ignites her gold coloured light saber defensively which abruptly stops Mara finishing her brothers name. Rey gazes more eagerly at the boy still not having learned his name who seeing her light saber Ignite excitedly reaches in and then drops his satchel.

Mara's who is standing protectively shoulder to shoulder with him now pleads 'don't try to force this she'll not buy anything, she's not like most people' but it's too late the boy is now standing innocently sure.if himself. Mara annoyingly pleads 'Abakin please' The boy, Anakin Antilles, looks up at Rey gesturing to her saber and says 'we've got one of those is it worth anything to you?'

Anakin then Ignites a green Light saber holding it steady and firm with the bright green glow reflecting off of the faces of the two teen siblings amidst the dark Tattonie red Sun's set.
End Movie Music!

Thoughts?

snippet.textDisplay: I enjoyed this movie, but it was such a mess. It seems that Abrams was trying to appease everyone, which is not a good thing. You know what was great about George Lucas? He didn't give a flying fuck about what people think about his movies, he wasn't trying to appease anyone, he was always making movies as he wanted. In fact, when Lucas started making "A New Hope", many people were laughing at him, but he didn't care, he finished his work, he released the movie and people loved it!  When he made "The Phantom Menace", many "fans" started insulting him, calling his creation  "a garbage", but Lucas didn't give a fuck! He finished the prequel trilogy, and you know what? It is great! The problem with "The Rise of Skywalker" is that JJ was trying to make both sides of Star Wars fanbase happy, but instead he made us all confused. I still like it, but I was expecting something better.

snippet.textDisplay: I didn't mind the movie, but I do agree the sudden introduction of Palpatine was a bit... eh? Yeah. Eh. Would have made more sense to have had him as sort of an echo within the movies, just maybe some whispers in The Force Awakens, maybe bring up a story about him in The Last Jedi, just you know.. put him into people's minds. And like Critic mentioned, after Snoke dies, have Palpatine just laugh in the distance/shadows... have glowy yellow eyes seen for a quick instance. THEN maybe the last movie might have had a better set up. I dunno. I enjoyed it as a film, but I didn't care for the story, and I am not a fan of the ending.
